  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Casual Composition
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ten years I've ridden through the dusty world, hurried and worn.
    One day of leisure comes—and idleness itself grows long.
    Morning wine warms me; gladly I surrender to its spell,
    And afternoon wind through my sleeves brings the breath of autumn.

    I cast off my cap, let my hair fall loose—let others laugh if they will.
    Seizing paper, I write my poems, deliberately playing the fool.
    How different from those days when duty calls me from the office,
    When my official robes are drenched through, sweat streaming like rivers.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'dusty world' (紅塵) is a Buddhist metaphor for the mundane realm of worldly affairs and desires.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'morning wine' and 'afternoon wind' create a progression through the day that moves from intoxication toward clarity and refreshment.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of sweat-soaked official robes contrasts sharply with the poet's present state of careless abandon, emphasizing the liberation found in this rare moment of freedom.
